  <h6>Materials</h6>
  <p>Gather markers<i>,</i> paper (a large sheet)<i>,</i> and stuffed animals or puppets</p>
  <h6>Share</h6>
  <p>Tell your child about something that used to scare you as a child (for example, a visit to the doctor, sirens, thunder). Ask for their advice: <i>What do you think I could have done to make myself feel less afraid?</i> Encourage suggestions, and write them down on a large piece of paper.</p>
  <h6>Role-play</h6>
  <p>Introduce a stuffed animal. Ask your child what the animal could be afraid of. Make the toy ask for advice: <i>How can I make myself feel less afraid?</i> Have your child offer ideas (such as cuddling with mom or dad or singing a favorite song). Next, have the toy act out some of the advice and report how it feels: <i>I feel better! Thanks</i>!</p>
  <h6>Talk about it</h6>
  <p>As your child grows, encourage talking about fears and finding ways to manage them.</p>
